			<p>The above is taken form our office Register. Thus you see<lb/> the whole matter left
				a balance of only &#36;91.47 out of<lb/> which to pay counsel fee in the <hi
					rend="underline">four</hi> suits&#8212;and I have<lb/> been able to reserve for
				myself but about &#36;10.</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
			<p>I give you all these figures that you may see <hi rend="underline">exactly</hi><lb/>
				how the matter has resulted&#44; as you might otherwise<lb/> have forgotten that
				there were any disbursements<lb/> to be made&#44; thinking only of the receipts&#58; for<lb/>
				<persName>Uncle David</persName> said to my mother while she was in
					<placeName>Phila</placeName><lb/> that &#8220;he had heard that <hi
					rend="underline">I</hi> had received &#36;100 from<lb/> one of your clients&#44;
				and as I had not sent you any<lb/> portion of it&#44; I must have enjoyed a fine
					<sic>yomtale</sic> with it.&#8221;<lb/> Of course I do not mind the remarks of
				third parties<lb/> but it is as well that things should be properly understood<lb/>
				and such remarks could not then be made.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I hope the books reached you safely. <persName>Frank</persName> has<lb/> one copy
				which he promised to send me&#44; but he has<lb/> failed to do so.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With <persName>Heller</persName> in <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> we can do
				nothing here.<lb/> A friend of mine has written me that he&#44;
					<persName>Heller</persName>&#44; is an<lb/> old man and very poor&#44; and
				nothing could be done with<lb/> him. If you are acquainted with a lawyer there<lb/>
				and are disposed to proceed against <persName>Heller</persName>. I can<lb/> furnish
				you with copies of the papers all ready prepared<lb/> which would save you much
				expense&#59; or if you desire<lb/> it&#44; <hi rend="underline">I</hi> will write
					<persName>Heller</persName> a very strong letter and<lb/> send him a copy of the
				printed report of the decision<lb/> of the Court in your suits against the parties
				in this city<lb/> which may have the effect of frightening him out of<lb/> the
				nefarious business and have the trouble and<lb/> expense of proceeding against him
				legally for an<lb/>
				<sic>an</sic> injunction. Please let me know your</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
			<p>wish&#44; and I shall be happy to do anything in my<lb/> power to serve you.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Fishel</persName> lectured to day to about a dozen or<lb/> two persons.
				The &#8220;Temple&#8221; however was crowded<lb/> when <persName><hi
						rend="underline">Dr.</hi> Adler</persName> held forth.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The new <sic>Portugese</sic> synagogue in <placeName>19<hi rend="sup">th</hi>
					St</placeName> is<lb/> progressing&#44; the front is entirely up&#44; and<lb/>
				presents a splendid appearance.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Shall we have the pleasure of seeing you<lb/> here this year&#63;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">My parents desire to be kindly remembered.<lb/> Father is suffering with his old
				complaint and<lb/> mother is not very well.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With best wishes for your health and<lb/> with continued feelings of the highest
				esteem and<lb/> friendly regard I remain Dr. Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Very truly yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">J. Solis Ritterband</persName></p>
			<p><placeName>No. 10 Wall St</placeName></p>
			<p>and</p>
